</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="81DC47DCFACAAF42CD77223BDC144E7B" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="A99D64916D3C2E973903B8D9DD4D3CEA" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName id="0B32CE9C1B20522BC0C5FE4CFE6CFE81" authorityName="Maddison &amp; Beattie &amp; Marathe &amp; Ng &amp; Kanesharatnam &amp; Benjamin &amp; Kunte" authorityYear="2020" class="Arachnida" family="Pittosporaceae" genus="Bavia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bavia smedleyi" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smedleyi" status="comb. nov.">Bavia smedleyi</taxonomicName>
Reimoser, 1929: 130-132, fig. 4, holotype female SMF 1127 in SMF from Siberut, Sumatra, examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5715CB6D2860F7E4A078B328FEF34118" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="notes">
<paragraph id="37095F01C984203596B11ADCD43F116B" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="95A6206556A136357C5FDC3E7F9581FE" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
This species is close to 
<taxonomicName id="2B362E626CC0423897DA5A04054B50BE" genus="M." lsidName="M. draconis" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="draconis">
<emphasis id="75CEB80DBF273985828533FDD562D149" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">M. draconis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with similar body form and markings (Figs 
<figureCitation id="399A5F5A4941CE3FA7EA46C1828B14D3" captionStart="Figures 225–228" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 225 - 228. Maripanthus smedleyi, female holotype (SMF 1127) 225 carapace 226 abdomen 227 epigyne, ventral 228 vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm; on body 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures225-228" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487555" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">225</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="8DCCC5658828A973F6353E189108E41B" captionStart="Figures 225–228" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 225 - 228. Maripanthus smedleyi, female holotype (SMF 1127) 225 carapace 226 abdomen 227 epigyne, ventral 228 vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm; on body 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures225-228" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487555" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">226</figureCitation>
), but differing in details of the epigyne (Figs 
<figureCitation id="EFF4CFBE0DB4D03CACD0D1346E2D2280" captionStart="Figures 225–228" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 225 - 228. Maripanthus smedleyi, female holotype (SMF 1127) 225 carapace 226 abdomen 227 epigyne, ventral 228 vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm; on body 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures225-228" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487555" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">227</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="77A6CF89C3A1C833AA38F22AC4B53D6D" captionStart="Figures 225–228" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 225 - 228. Maripanthus smedleyi, female holotype (SMF 1127) 225 carapace 226 abdomen 227 epigyne, ventral 228 vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm; on body 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures225-228" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487555" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">228</figureCitation>
). The atria are shorter, ~ 
<normalizedToken id="79F498A8DC59ABD478313B2F238E47BD" originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
length of the epigyne. Within the atria, the central depressed area is separated from the lateral raised areas by a more distinct and more heavily sclerotized &quot;atrial cliff&quot; (
<normalizedToken id="884F758BF35F45BDAB582E9A775FE252" originalValue="“ac”">&quot;ac&quot;</normalizedToken>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="114848A994E9AD9CD63518DB00D23415" captionStart="Figures 225–228" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 225 - 228. Maripanthus smedleyi, female holotype (SMF 1127) 225 carapace 226 abdomen 227 epigyne, ventral 228 vulva, dorsal. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm; on body 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures225-228" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487555" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">227</figureCitation>
). The spermathecae are smaller.
</paragraph>
